===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|angle|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|angulus||corner, remote area|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*ang-||corner, hirn}}. Cognate with {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|ancha||nape of the neck|lang=goh}}, {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{term|anke||joint of the foot, nape of neck|lang=gmh}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|angl|es}}

# {{context|transitive|often in the [[passive]]|lang=en}} To place (something) at an angle.
#: ''The roof is '''angled''' at 15 degrees.''
# {{context|intransitive|informal|lang=en}} To change direction rapidly.
#: ''The five ball '''angled''' off the nine ball but failed to reach the pocket.''
# {{context|transitive|informal|lang=en}} To present or argue something in a particular way or from a particular viewpoint.
#: ''How do you want to '''angle''' this when we talk to the client?''
# {{context|snooker|lang=en}} To leave the cue ball in the jaws of a pocket such that the surround of the pocket (the "angle") blocks the path from cue ball to object ball.

